==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Distain
<hw>Dis*tain"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Distained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Distaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>desteinen</ets>, OF. <ets>desteindre</ets> to take away the color,
F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧teindre</ets>; pref. <ets>des-</ets> (L.
<ets>dis-</ets>) + F. <ets>teindre</ets> to tinge, dye, L.
<ets>tingere</ets>. See <er>Tinge</er>, and cf. <er>Stain</er>.]</ety>
<def>To tinge with a different color from the natural or proper one; to
stain; to discolor; to sully; to tarnish; to defile; -- used chiefly in
poetry.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Distained</xex> with dirt and blood.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[She] hath . . . <qex>distained</qex> her honorable blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The worthiness of praise <qex>distains</qex> his worth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Distal</ent>⟦br⟧
